/r/AdvancedRunning - An analysis of race reports


What is /r/AdvancedRunning?

/r/AdvancedRunning is an online forum “for runners who love the sport of running and all its aspects”.
The prefix Advanced does not imply only fast runners are welcomed. There is no required pace or distance to join in on the discussion at /r/advancedrunning, only the love of the sport and aspect of running.

What is a race report?

Race reports are own accounts of races, where runners describe their training, goals for the race, how the race went, etc.
The picture below shows an example of a race report.


The Data

The main data for analysis includes a total of 900 race reports from /r/AdvancedRunning and /r/artc (another running forum used mostly by old members of /r/AdvancedRunning).
For comparison purposes, we will also see the results of 500 race reports from /r/running. /r/running is a forum dedicated to less experienced runners.
Results from big marathons (Lisbon, London, Boston, etc) will be used to compare AdvancedRunners to the overall population of world marathoners.

Race details

When does /r/advancedrunning race?

AdvancedRunners race mostly in the Spring (from March to May) and in Autumn (October and November), when conditions are better for racing. Of course, most races are held in these months, so runners are also more likely to chose these months for their races.

How fast is /r/advancedrunning?

Distribution of marathon results

Standing out above all other times, a marathon time between 02:55:00 and 03:00:00 is the most common race time. Running a marathon under 3 hours is a very common goal for advanced runners. 3 hours is a round number, a very challenging time, and in addition, it’s about the time needed to be able to qualify for the Boston Marathon. 15 people have run below 02:35. The distribution has a long right tail, but not may runners go over 4 hours for their marathons.

Does /r/AdvancedRunning achieve their goals?

Race result vs goal

On this chart we plotted the goals of each race on the xx axis, and the actual result from that race on the yy axis.
We previously saw that most goals are times multiple of 5 minutes (03:00:00, 03:05:00, etc), so that’s why on this chart we almost can see vertical lines of points. The diagonal plotted separates the people who achieved their goals (coloured in green) to the people who did not achieve their goals (coloured in red).
The higher a runner is from the line, the more they beat their time. Conversely, the lower from the line, the more distance they were from their goal.
